ENTRY            L0293   20260423   20260617   20260617       L059
SUBENT        L0293001   20260423   20260617   20260617       L059
BIB                 13         76
TITLE      Measurements of short-lived fission product yields
           from photofission of 238U using 13.0 MeV monoenergetic
           photons
AUTHOR     (I.Tsorxe,S.W.Finch,C.R.Howell,Krishichayan,
           A.P.D.Ramirez,J.A.Silano,A.P.Tonchev,W.Tornow)
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,113,024603,2026)
           #doi:10.1103/57zl-ks5z
REL-REF    (O,L0225001,Krishichayan+,J,PR/C,100,014608,2019)
           235,238U and 239Pu data
           (O,L0221001,M.Bhike+,J,PR/C,95,024608,2017) 239Pu data
INSTITUTE  (1USANCS,1USATNL,1USADKE,1USALRL)
FACILITY   (ESTRG,1USADKE) High Intensity Gamma Source (HIgS)
           Facility on the campus of Duke University.
INC-SOURCE (LCS) A high-flux photon beam is created by colliding
           relativistic electron beam bunches, circulating in a
           storage ring, with photon pulses inside the
           high-power optical cavity of a free-electron laser
            (FEL). The average electron beam current and energy
           were 100 mA and 623 MeV, respectively. The FEL photon
           wavelength was 546.5 nm, which resulted in a
           13.0+0.22-0.25 MeV photon beam. The photon beam was
           shaped upstream of the 238U target using an aluminum
           collimator of length 44.5 cm with a circular hole of
           1.90 cm in diameter.
DETECTOR   (HPGE,NAICR,FISCH) The photon beam energy spectrum
           was measured with a 110% coaxial high-purity germanium
            (HPGe) detector and a large cylindrical (25 cm
           diameter x 35 cm length) NaI detector, both of which
           were positioned in the beam path downstream of the
           target irradiation location.
SAMPLE     (92-U-238,ENR=0.99974) In order to determine the total
           fission rate in the thick 238U activation target, the
           measured fission rate in the DFC is scaled by the mass
           ratio of the thin-to-thick 238U targets. Both the thick
            and thin targets are 1.27 cm in diameter. Masses and
           isotopic purity of the 238U target and reference foils
           installed in the dual fission chamber (DFC).
           Foil       Mass                  Isotopic purity (%)
           DFC 1      124.3(16) microg      99.998
           DFC 2      136.7(18) microg      99.998
           Target     441.0(1)  mg          99.974
METHOD     (ACTIV) The fission rate in the target is determined
           from in-beam measurements made using a dual fission
           chamber (DFC) containing thin foils of the same nucleus
            of which the 238U target is made. Short-lived FPYs
           were measured by performing cyclic activation of the
           sample using a rapid target transfer system.
           Following activation, the 238U target was rapidly
            (0.4 s) transferred to a counting station consisting
           of two well-shielded high-purity germanium detectors.
           The irradiation-counting cycle was repeated until the
           summed data had sufficient statistical accuracy.
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-S) Photopeak area and fission chamber counts.
           (ERR-SYS) Systematic uncertainty (all other sources,
           added in quadrature).
           (ERR-1) Thick target mass.
           (ERR-2) DFC reference foil masses.
           (ERR-3,0.,12.) gamma-ray intensity.
           (ERR-4) HPGe detector efficiency.
           (ERR-5) Fission chamber efficiency.
           (ERR-6,0.18,5.6) Half-life.
           (ERR-7) gamma-ray absorption.
           (ERR-8) Cycle timing.
           (ERR-9) Summing correction.
           (ERR-10) DFC and target alignment.
CORRECTION The self-attenuation correction accounts for photons
           absorbed by the target itself. This correction is
           typically <1% for the thin target used. In addition,
           a correction was applied to account for any
           fluctuations from the strict timing cycle of the
           cyclic activation equation. Once again, this
           correction was typically <1%. Lastly, coincidence
           summing corrections were applied using the algorithm
           of truecoinc. The summing correction factors for this
           experiment were typically found to be <3%.
HISTORY    (20260423C) BP
ENDBIB              76
